4 HJR198 ESTABLISHING THE ALABAMA MENTAL HEALTH TASK FORCE.
5
6 WHEREAS, millions of adults and children are affected
7 by mental illnesses every year; and
8 WHEREAS, individuals with mental illnesses lead full,
9 productive lives when they have access to necessary
10 treatment, services, and support in their communities; and
11 WHEREAS, only half of individuals with a serious form
12 of mental illness seek treatment for their mental illness;
13 and
14 WHEREAS, stigma and fear of discrimination keep many
15 who would benefit from mental health services from seeking
16 help; and
17 WHEREAS, greater public awareness about mental
18 illnesses can reduce stigma and change negative attitudes
19 and behaviors toward individuals with mental illnesses; and
20 WHEREAS, the Legislature is positioned to enhance
21 public awareness of mental illness and improve access to
22 mental health care in this state; now therefore,
23 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
24 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That there is created the Alabama
25 Mental Health Task Force to evaluate and recommend long-term
26 policies and solutions for improving mental health care in
27 this state.
Page 1

this state.
HJR198 Engrossed
28 (a) The membership of the task force shall consist of
29 the following:
30 (1) One psychiatrist appointed by the Governor.
31 (2) One clinical psychologist appointed by the
32 Lieutenant Governor.
33 (3) One member of the House of Representatives
34 appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives and
35 one member of the House of Representatives appointed by the
36 Minority Leader of the House of Representatives.
37 (4) One member of the Senate appointed by the
38 President Pro Tempore of the Senate and one member of the
39 Senate appointed by the Minority Leader of the Senate.
40 (5) The Chair of the Senate Finance and Taxation
41 General Fund Committee, or his or her designee.
42 (6) The Chair of the House of Representatives Ways
43 and Means General Fund Committee, or his or her designee.
44 (7) The Commissioner of the Alabama Department of
45 Mental Health, or his or her designee.
46 (8) The State Health Officer, or his or her designee.
47 (9) One member appointed by the Alabama Probate
48 Judges Association.
49 (b) The appointing authorities shall coordinate their
50 appointments to assure the task force membership is
51 inclusive and reflects the racial, gender, geographic,
52 urban, rural, and economic diversity of the state.
53 (c) The work of the task force may include, but is
54 not limited to, any of the following in pursuit of its goal
55 of evaluating and recommending long-term policies and
Page 2

of evaluating and recommending long-term policies and
HJR198 Engrossed
56 solutions to improve mental health care in this state:
57 (1) Collecting and analyzing data related to the
58 current state of mental health care across the state.
59 (2) Evaluating the resources currently available to
60 address mental health conditions and identifying the gaps in
61 those resources.
62 (3) Developing mental health intervention programs to
63 help Alabamians identify, understand, and respond to signs
64 of mental health disorders in themselves and among their
65 peers.
66 (4) Exploring the impact of mental health conditions
67 on education, employment, and public safety.
68 (5) Reviewing and identifying gaps in current mental
69 health training and professional development provided to
70 public health personnel for identification, referral,
71 intervention, and prevention of mental health conditions.
72 (6) Reviewing the workforce landscape to determine if
73 there are sufficient personnel to address the mental health
74 conditions of the state.
75 (7) Developing long-term goals for mental health
76 resources and care in the state.
77 (d) The first meeting of the task force shall be held
78 at the call of the Governor no later than 30 days after this
79 resolution's passage, at which time the task force shall
80 elect a chair and vice chair. The task force may then meet
81 as necessary to conduct business.
82 (e) The Legislative Services Agency, the Clerk of the
83 House of Representatives, the Secretary of the Senate, the
Page 3

House of Representatives, the Secretary of the Senate, the
HJR198 Engrossed
84 Alabama Department of Public Health, and the Alabama
85 Department of Mental Health shall provide administrative and
86 other assistance for the work of the task force as
87 necessary.
88 (f)(1) The legislative members of the task force
89 shall be entitled to their legislative compensation, per
90 diem, and travel expenses for each day they attend a meeting
91 of the task force pursuant to Section 49 of the Constitution
92 of Alabama of 2022.
93 (2) The nonlegislative members of the task force
94 shall serve without compensation but may be reimbursed for
95 necessary expenses in attending meetings of the task force
96 pursuant to the policies of their respective appointing
97 authority.
98 (g) The task force shall prepare and submit a final
99 report of its findings, conclusions, and recommendations to
100 the Legislature no later than November 1, 2026. Upon filing
101 its report with the Legislature, the task force shall stand
102 dissolved and discharged of any future duties and
103 liabilities.
104 (h) Pursuant to Section 36-14-17.1, Code of Alabama
105 1975, the task force shall provide to the Secretary of State
106 a notice of all meetings, the name of each member serving on
107 the task force, and a copy of the final report and other
108 documents produced throughout the duration of the task
109 force.
110 (i) Each appointing authority named herein shall be
111 provided a copy of this resolution upon its passage.
